ay not be the optimal solution. For example, the Travelling Salesman Problem (TSP).\r\n\r\n','Heuristic method',2,35,22,NULL,NULL,'Heuristics','2019-02-21 07:14:48',1,1),(574,'Define the term Divide and Conquer','\r\n\r\n','Divide and conquer',1,35,22,NULL,NULL,'Divide and Conq','2019-02-21 07:21:06',1,1),(575,'Describe the use of the Divide and Conquer technique','An example of a Divide and Conquer technique is a binary search. Given an ordered list, it splits the list in half then decides which half of the list to search and which half it can discard. It will do this repeatedly until it finds the item being searched.\r\n','Divide and conquer,Binary search',2,35,22,NULL,NULL,'Divide and Conq','2019-02-21 07:25:51',1,1),(576,'Define the term Linear search','','Linear search',1,36,1,3,NULL,'','2019-03-02 08:49:17',1,1),(577,'Define the term Binary search','\r\n\r\n','Binary search,Divide and conquer',1,36,1,3,NULL,'','2019-03-02 08:49:57',1,1),(578,'Construct a linear search algorithm','Write or complete a linear search algorithm.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','Linear search',4,36,1,NULL,NULL,'','2019-03-03 09:07:50',1,1),(579,'Construct a binary search algorithm','Write or complete a binary search algorithm or show the detailed steps involved in finding an item in a list using a binary search algorithm.\r\n\r\n','Binary search',4,36,1,NULL,NULL,'','2019-03-03 09:09:06',1,1),(580,'Construct a bubble sort algorithm','Write or complete a bubble sort algorithm                    \r\n','Bubble sort',4,36,1,NULL,NULL,'','2019-03-03 09:17:11',1,1),(581,'Construct a merge sort algorithm','Complete the step of a merge sort algorithm\r\n','Merge sort',4,36,1,NULL,NULL,'','2019-03-03 09:18:27',1,1),(582,'Construct an insertion sort algorithm','Complete an insertion sort algorithm\r\n','Insertion sort',4,36,1,NULL,NULL,'','2019-03-03 09:19:42',1,1),(583,'Define the term subroutine','','Subroutine,Function,Procedure',1,48,19,NULL,NULL,'','2019-03-09 04:26:44',1,1),(584,'Describe what a subroutine is and the different types','Subroutines are blocks of code within a program that are written to carry out a task. There are two types of subroutines: Functions that return a value and a Procedure that carries out a task without returning a value. Subroutines can accept one or more parameters.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','Subroutine,Function,Procedure,Parameter',2,48,19,NULL,NULL,'','2019-03-09 04:31:58',1,1),(585,'Explain the purpose of subroutines and how they used within a program','A subroutine can exist anywhere in the program but is not executed until it is called using it\"s identifier.  They are used to break down a program into manageable sections. The subroutine can be called multiple times within a program, preventing the program from having duplicate code. This allows the subroutine to be modified only once.\r\n\r\nA subroutine accepts inputs called parameters to determine the execution of the code.\r\n\r\nThere are two types of subroutines: functions and procedures. A function will return a value to the section of code and a procedure carries out a task, but does not return a value.\r\n','Subroutine,Function,Procedure,Identifier names',3,48,19,NULL,NULL,'','2019-03-09 04:45:43',1,1),(586,'Give an account of how local and global variables are used within a program','Variables defined in the main program are called Global variables that can be used anywhere in the program, whereas variables defined within a subroutine are called local variables and cannot be used outside of the subroutine unless they are defined as global. A variable is said to have global and local scope. Find examples of global and local variables.\r\n','Variable,Local variable,Global variable',2,48,19,NULL,NULL,'','2019-03-09 05:07:11',1,1),(587,'Construct a program that uses subroutines using parameters, local variables and global variables','Your program should use global and local variables. Create subroutines that use parameters instead of global variables. Create a function instead of 